   <abstract>Writing studies has witnessed a growing enthusiasm for design thinking (Leverenz; Marback; Purdy; Wible), yet little disciplinary attention has been paid to its role and application in collaborative, interdisciplinary support spaces such as writing centers. In writing centers, design thinking as a methodology could represent a useful support option for at least three reasons: its emphasis on multimodal and creative problem-solving, attention to materiality, and encouragement of interdisciplinary collaboration. Therefore, this dissertation examines design thinking's potential significance for writing centers, many of which have modified their approaches to meet the demands of multimodal communication and working with students across the disciplines. This study was guided by the following research questions: 1. Is design thinking a factor in postsecondary writing centers? If so, to what extent and in what forms does design thinking figure in those sites? 2. What are the situational factors that facilitate or inhibit the inclusion of design thinking in writing centers? 3. How, if employed, is design thinking conceptualized? 4. How, if employed, is design thinking introduced, applied, and supported? To respond to these questions, the study used a nationally distributed survey and three programmatic case studies of postsecondary writing centers that have considered design thinking for their local contexts. First, the study's findings revealed that pursuing conversations about design thinking in writing centers may be generative yet wide-ranging since stakeholders will bring different visions and uses for design thinking. Therefore, it may be more useful to describe design thinking's potential for writing centers in terms of where it falls on a spectrum of contextual influences. Second, from an administrative standpoint, there are options to think about how design thinking could factor into writing center operations whether as a guiding philosophy (principles, pedagogies, curriculum) or as one aspect of many practices that can encourage different forms of individual or collaborative work (Berry and Dieterle; Gresham and Yancey; Lee and Carpenter; Schwemmle et al.). Third, in working with writers across disciplines, design thinking could facilitate discussions about multimodal communication in different subject areas such as general science, engineering, and arts education.</abstract>
